fields.physical_description:
Twenty three miscellaneous items assembled for the playing of 'Kim's game': the items are displayed for a brief time and removed, when the participants are required to list them from memory.
[tin] Snap-on lid of a tin which originally contained adhesive tape, made of mild pressed steel, enamel coated in bright turquoise, white and black on the exterior.  Used with B.23:2-1999
[tin] Base of a tin which originally contained adhesive tape, made of mild pressed steel, enamel coated in bright turquoise on the exterior.  Used with B.23:1-1999
[cork] Champagne cork, in the traditional waisted bulbous-topped shape, of cork with a rounded metal top
[rubber piece] Untrimmed scrap of red rubber sheeting
[notice] Milk bottle notice, ovoid in shape, with a circular hole to fit around the bottle neck.  The lettering is in white on a turquoise ground.
[paintbrush] Paint or glue brush, with coarse bristles set into a crimped metal mount and unvarnished cylindrical wooden handle
[toggle] Beechwood toggle with tapering curved ends and waisted middle
[string piece] Length of white cotton fibre string wound into a small bundle
[whistle] Whistle (probably a cracker toy) of pressed tin, in the form of two domed discs conjoined, and extending into a straight-sided mouthpiece
[cork] Flat topped cork stopper with tapering sides
[button] Domed boot/ shoe button of black composition with a metal shank at the back
[button] Domed boot/ shoe button of black composition with a metal shank at the back
[screw] Brass alloy screw with counter-sunk head
[graphite pencil] Lead pencil stump, with wooden casing painted yellow and stamped in silver with the trade name and type in silver coloured pigment.
[pen top] Removable cap for a ballpoint pen, of red plastic in the form of a curved cone with a self clip.
[pen top] Removable cap for a ballpoint pen, of royal blue plastic in the form of a curved cone with a self clip.
[Halfpenny] 1908 halfpenny coin, with the head of Edward VII on the obverse, and Britannia on the reverse
[Penny] 1936 penny coin, with the head of George V on the obverse, and Britannia on the reverse
[Farthing] 1937 farthing coin, with the head of George VI on the obverse, and the wren on the reverse
[paper sheet] Cut piece of feint ruled and numbered white paper, folded and hand written with the name of the game.
